<Document>
<name>Atherton Tablelands Loop</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Atherton Tablelands Loop</h2><p><i>Queensland, Australia · Cairns hinterland loop via Mareeba, Atherton, Millaa Millaa, Innisfail</i></p><p><b>Cairns' cool-country backyard — waterfall circuit, volcanic crater lakes, dairy farms, rainforest curtain figs.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>246 km (153 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>Full day; ideally 2 days</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Year-round; June–October driest; February–April for fullest waterfalls</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Steep range climb on the Gillies Highway (260+ corners); cassowaries on road south of Mission Beach; wet season showers any time of year</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>548</td></tr></table><hr><p>The Tablelands are a high basalt plateau (700–1,100 m) west of Cairns — cool-country dairy farms, tropical fruit orchards, and waterfall after waterfall where streams running off the plateau drop over the basalt edge. The Gillies Range Road climbs from the coast in 260+ corners — the most-twisting sealed road in Queensland. Volcanic crater lakes (Eacham, Barrine) are perfectly circular blue eyes set in dripping rainforest. The Curtain Fig at Yungaburra is a strangler fig that took root in a leaning host tree, sending a 15 m sheet of aerial roots straight down — one of Australia's strangest plants. Platypus swim in Peterson Creek at dusk. The waterfall circuit (Millaa Millaa, Zillie, Ellinjaa) takes an hour and is required.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Kuranda</b> — Rainforest village reached by either the 1891 Kuranda Scenic Railway (15 tunnels through gorge country) or the Skyrail cable car gliding above the canopy. Markets daily.</li><li><b>Mareeba — coffee and mango country</b> — Drier rainshadow side of the range — Australia's coffee belt and most of its mango exports. Skybury and Jaques estates do tours; Granite Gorge nearby is a wild rock-wallaby colony.</li><li><b>Curtain Fig Tree</b> — 500-year-old strangler fig whose host tree fell at an angle, leaving the fig's aerial roots as a 15 m vertical curtain to the forest floor. Boardwalk loop (5 minutes).</li><li><b>Lake Eacham</b> — Crater lake in dense rainforest — 65 m deep, formed by a phreatic eruption ~9,000 years ago. Swimming, picnic ground, 3 km loop walk. Snake-necked turtles in the shallows.</li><li><b>Millaa Millaa Falls</b> — 18 m horsetail falls dropping into a green pool — the most-photographed waterfall in Australia. The hair-flick photograph belongs to a thousand backpackers. Continue the 16 km loop to Zillie and Ellinjaa Falls.</li><li><b>Babinda Boulders</b> — Granite-bouldered swimming hole (warning: drowning blackspot — swim only the upper Devil's Pool only at posted depths). The Yidinji legend behind the place is darker than the brochure version.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
